##Out of the shelter, the gap in the transition of ordinary people | Wuhan scene

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. Back to the outside world, some people and police saw, some neighbors said "toxic" , some miss the cabin time, some began a new life

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Liu Yiqin, CAIJING reporter

Editor | Sheryl Rong

On the afternoon of March 4, L Ti (not his real name) , a resident of Wuhan's Qiao Estuary, was informed that he could be discharged from the shelter. He was admitted to the Jiangxia District Shelter Hospital in Wuhan, where he needed to return to the Qiaokou District area for rehabilitation and isolation due to territorial management.

At 3 pm, three transfer buses carrying him and dozens of other patients, arrived at the gate of Xinhua printing factory in the Qiao estuary. The workers carried out a simple renovation in advance of the printing factory, covering it with bedsheets and electric blankets.

Factory building is very old, mottled walls, after the renovation of the factory is more like a small shelter, a bed with a public mobile toilet outside, to go on a road.

L TI did not want to live here, "everyone is crowded together, there is no independent bathroom, if cross-infection? It is better to live in a shelter, " he expressed concern to Caijing reporters.

Some accepted and got out of the CAR; others refused to get out and asked to be moved to a better isolation point. There was an altercation. The tug-of-war continues into the evening, with police from the Qiao estuary rushing to the scene to maintain order, persuade them to understand and move in as soon as possible.

At night, when the temperature dropped, the two sides remained deadlocked. Some of the extravehicular patients were ready to sleep directly in the car, because "once you get in, you can't get out again. " But the car was so cold that they ran to the medical staff's office to sit down, and refused to move in.

The police were very helpless. A police officer at the scene told Caijing that all the hotels that could be commandeered in the Qiao estuary have been commandeered, mainly for the accommodation of rescue teams from outside, and some are used to isolate suspected personnel and close contacts, "Now that we're full, we can't kick them out of the hotel. It's the best we can do. "

Outside the building were boxes of electric blankets, which the police said had been laid overnight by volunteers who opened them before patients could be transported, fearing they would freeze. "It's so hard now, why can't everyone understand each other? "

On February 3, Wuhan announced the opening of a shelter hospital. In the past month or so, countless people have paid close attention to life in the shelter. On February 23,14 shelter hospitals opened 12,165 beds and 8,689 patients in the hospital during the month of the city's closure, one out of every four confirmed cases in Wuhan has been treated in a shelter.

There's a lot going on in the shelter. Mr. Fu, who was reading in his hospital bed at Douyinli, went overseas and staged a real-life version of "reading is a shelter you can take with you at any time. " Bahaguli, a medical worker with the Xinjiang medical team, led the patients in a Xinjiang dance, giving depressed patients a "shot in the arm" and allaying worries, a senior in a Wuchang shelter was preparing for an exam when doctors set up a temporary study room for her, and patients in the shelter scrambled to post photos of their meals, there are meat and vegetables, Fruit Yogurt, and even appeared abalone, Turtle.

On March 10, with the Wembley Arena and the dahuashan shelter in Jiangxia District, and the 20 or so shelters in Wuhan, most of them were discharged from the hospital, most of them recovered, and a few were transferred to a hospital with beds for further treatment. Patients outside the capsule also need to focus on isolation observation for 14 days, if their physical condition is stable, they can go home isolation for 14 days, if there is no abnormal situation, they can return to normal life.

The shelter closure, for society and most people, means a milestone in the fight against the epidemic, but for some people, out of the shelter, is a new battle.

A tug-of-war after the hatch

There is nothing wrong with the patient's basic requirements for isolation; there is nothing wrong with the civilian police

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 1 am on March 5, a Qiaokou District policeman got up from his bed and hurried to the door of the printing factory, where a dozen policemen were already on the scene. One of the volunteers worried about the situation of the extravehicular patients, helped to contact the epidemic prevention headquarters, the other said that the district chief has rushed to deal with it.

A police officer at the scene told Caijing that the district chief was there and the head of the public security was there. The police at the scene refused to let the CAIJING reporter in for interviews. In another old factory building outside the quarantine zone, some staff members stared at the monitoring screen to observe the movement inside.

Several police officers in protective suits repeatedly went in to communicate, and at one point there was an argument. "The government has done its best, " said a police officer, who was pointed at by an extravehicular patient. "The patient's food costs more than 130 yuan a day. We are on duty day and night, and we rarely eat meat. "

Some patients have asked for single rooms, and hotels have run out of rooms. Even small hotels with 20 rooms have been requisitioned. L Ti found that there were also small rooms converted from containers, with a bed inside, but "the smell is very strong, live in fear of poisoning. "

In addition to hotels, but also to meet the conditions of a person to live in a room, that is, universities and staff quarters, but the Qiao estuary resources are limited, not too many universities.

CAIJING asked why patients could not be placed in other resource-rich areas of isolation? The police responded that they were now strictly territorial, and that they had asked similar questions, but that other districts would not say whether they had vacancies, that information was not available, or that they would not receive patients from other districts.

In Wuhan, Wuchang District and Qingshan District, Wuhan Hotel resources are relatively rich, Hongshan District and Jiangxia District school resources are relatively large. Several of Jiangxia District's extravehicular patients told Caijing that they were living in an isolated area of the school's dormitory. A Wuchang District government official said that there are still hotels open in Wuchang District and would consider keeping them if the number of discharged patients needed to be quarantined was high.

On the morning of March 5, the tug of war at the New China printing plant was finally over. Some of the patients who had to be housed in single rooms were transferred to other isolation points and moved into single container rooms. L Ti stayed at the printing plant because some of the patients were moved, he moved into the original arrangement of more than 10 people in the area, "is also a separate living. "

Some of the patient's basic requirements for isolation may seem reasonable. What the police do is far from problematic. In special periods, such tug-of-war occurs from time to time. A little more mutual understanding seems especially extravagant at this time. Some police shift at 4 am, 8 am to continue the new day on duty, just past the tug-of-war does not seem to have much impact on them: "This is our normal work, accustomed to. "

L Ti lived in a quarantine zone, and no new patients were brought in. He said the food at the isolation point was a little worse than in the cabin, but it was fine. Doctors would come by regularly to check on him and take his temperature. Everything was fine, he said. "I just want to go home and be with my family. "

Nobody wants to go back to the hospital

No one wants to go through the process again. It's like a monster upgrade, back to square one when you're so close to winning

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On March 10, Wang Di received a notice to leave the isolation point and go home.

Wang's grandparents had been diagnosed, and her mother was later admitted to the shelter. Although he had no symptoms, he thought he might have been hit, but the community workers were so overwhelmed, he went to multiple hospitals, applied for a nucleic acid test, tested positive, and the CT showed no lung infection.

On Feb. 9, he was taken to a shelter hospital, but because he had no symptoms, Wang quickly underwent two more nucleic acid tests, both negative, and on Feb. 25, he was told he could leave the cabin.

He was sent to a dormitory at the Yangtze Vocational College in Wuhan, which was converted into a rehabilitation center with separate bathrooms for each person. On the morning of Feb. 26, he showered and stood on the balcony, breathing heavily and taking off his mask. At that moment, he said, he felt very happy.

Wang has always wondered if he really has a new coronary pneumonia, except for the first positive nucleic acid test, then 4 nucleic acid tests were negative. At the quarantine point, he counted the days until he got home. One day, he saw a notice in the wechat group, and he lives on the same floor of another GRANDPA, check out Fuyang.

To protect the patient's privacy, no one knew which room the patient was in. He saw an ambulance and community workers coming, but the patient refused to return to the hospital, "He doesn't want to go through the process again, " he said. "It's like a monster upgrade. He's back to square one when he's so close to winning. "

On March 8, Fu Huihua, a resident of Qingshan District, Wuhan, told doctors at the quarantine point hotel that she had been suffering from abdominal pain for several days. Fu Huihua, who tested positive for nucleic acid on February 12, was admitted to the shelter hospital. On February 28, he left the cabin and entered the hotel for isolation. On March 4, she felt sick, abdominal pain, fatigue and could not eat.

She was afraid to tell the doctors and her family that she didn't want to go to the hospital anymore. Until March 8th, when it was too much to bear, and told the doctor.

Quarantine point arranged for a vehicle to take her to the hospital for examination, first went to Qingshan District, Wuhan Po Yan Hospital, found lung infection, bile inflammation, doctors concluded that pneumonia has not yet recovered, but po Yan Hospital is not a designated hospital, do not accept. After the quarantine site was reported to the Epidemic Prevention Headquarters, it was sent to the Ninth Hospital in Wuhan. The doctors of the Ninth Hospital said that because Fu Huihua's nucleic acid was negative and did not meet the hospital's criteria, the designated hospital could only accept patients who were nucleic acid positive.

Until 8 pm on March 11, Fu Huihua was admitted to the Wuhan Iron and Steel Hospital. At 3 pm on March 12, Fu Huihua told Caijing that she was preparing for further examination.

"CAIJING" reporter learned that in the different recovery isolation point, the situation of medical duty varies. Some patients reported daily visits from their doctors, while others said they had heard of a doctor but had not seen him for several days, with only the food delivery staff taking temperature notes along the way.

A patient who was quarantined by the Yangtze River Engineering University in Jiangxia District wanted an antibody test. He felt relieved after checking the antibody after a case of him being discharged from hospital and recovering from Yang had appeared. He called the mayor's hotline and received a reply: Wuhan has no regulations for the work of drawing blood at isolation points to check for antibodies, so it can not be arranged for the time being.

I miss the "family. "

He walked into the community gate, met some come out to take express delivery, buy food neighbors, someone said, "how this kind of people also put back. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang was young and had no symptoms at all, and spent his days in the shelter actively organizing his fellow passengers to help each other, including helping nurses with meals and caring for his grandfather, who has Alzheimer's disease. One day, the nurse who was examining everyone in the shelter suddenly fainted because of low blood sugar. The other nurses could not carry it. Several male patients immediately rushed to help carry the fainting nurse to the outdoor ventilation area and immediately stood far away, get the nurses to help.

Zhang Jie, who was hospitalized in the same shelter as Wang, was mainly responsible for caring for his Alzheimer's grandfather, who was in his 70s. According to the shelter's requirements, only mild cases between the ages of 18 and 65 could be admitted, the age limit can be relaxed if a family member enters the shelter in isolation, but the grandfather came alone.

They tried to contact his family, his eldest son is seriously ill, in the Thor Mountain Hospital treatment, the younger son, although very worried about his father, but refused to video-chat with his father, GRANDPA's wife has also been diagnosed, in another shelter.

Wang Di Remembers, GRANDPA was often sitting crying, said here are bad people, do not let him out, one day GRANDPA himself secretly ran out, trying to break the outside barbed wire escape.

Zhang and several other older sisters took turns taking care of GRANDPA, helping him to fetch water, wash his face and feet, feed him, and taking GRANDPA for a walk. Because of the experience of trying to escape, the staff did not allow GRANDPA to go outside. Wang Di and staff communication, said he took GRANDPA outside to walk, to ensure that no problem.

February 25, Wang di out of the cabin, from the hospital bed all the way to the door, all give him greeting, send blessing, has gone out he also heard someone shouted: "Congratulations, we are coming! "

He was happy to get in the van, but began to miss it. "It's like family in the shelter. "

Dr. Wang said that psychologists were stationed in both the shelter and the isolation point to help patients, but that some patients did not think it would be useful. "How can they understand the patients' psychology if they have not been infected? "

On March 10, Wang Di was told that because of two consecutive negative nucleic acid tests, he would be released from quarantine and sent home. A transport van dropped him off at the community gate and he walked in on his own. There were also some residents who had come out to pick up express delivery and buy vegetables. He heard someone say, "How can such a person be put back? "

While community workers won't reveal which homes are infected, neighbors will notice when they are picked up, disinfected, and left unattended for long periods of time. A patient who was released from quarantine went home to his community group, and a neighbor said not to put his group dishes together for fear of poisoning.

The new shelter will be operational

This will be used for the treatment of patients and suspected cases in the isolation prison, the end of the war began

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On March 11, more than 300 containers were placed at a construction site in Jiangxia District, Wuhan, where workers were rushing to finish a water purification plant that needed to be delivered at 8 pm, it's about 30 kilometers from the heart of Wuhan.

CAIJING reporters at the scene saw that the center isolation area was surrounded by high barbed wire, four corners have mobile toilets and public sink, each container placed a bed.

Zhang Qihui, a worker on the site, had also been involved in the construction of other shelters. His partner, Hu, had been involved in the construction of Thor Mountain, which was used to treat patients and suspected cases in the isolation prison, they told CAIJING.

It's not the biggest shelter currently under construction, he said, adding that Caidian District has an even bigger one. I hear there's a lot of people in need of isolation in prison, and 300 containers isn't enough.

At 6 pm, Zhang Qihui left the site. Workers from the Logistics Department continued to finish up the work. They also needed to lay out the quilts and put away the daily necessities.

Workers will be paid 100 yuan an hour at the end of the day to participate in the construction of the isolation point. Lunch boxes will be distributed at the scene, there are meat and vegetables, masks are issued daily new, there are three times a day temperature checks and disinfection, some workers feel, out to work than at home to stay safe, well-paid.

On the afternoon of March 11, more lorries and containers were being brought in at the gate of the Hanyang Prison in Wuhan. The workers at the gate told Caijing that the containers were used to isolate patients in the prison and had not yet been opened for use.

Similar "shelter" is still in the construction, delivery, but there is no public information statistics, most of them are located in the suburbs, or the old factory renovation. The other shelter he was involved in was in an industrial park in the east-west Lake district, about 30 km from the Wuhan Centre, outside the Fourth Ring Road, where there are 1,000 beds.

On March 12, in a cloudy day in Wuhan, the results of the 11 days he had been out of the cabin were negative, and he calculated that he had only three days left to go home; Wang Di received a peace offering from a community worker; and Zhang Qihui returned to his residence, waiting for the next announcement of the start of the new shelter. Every time he left the finished shelter, he would take photos as a memento. He felt very happy to do something for Wuhan during the special period, "Then I want to go to the Pak Sha Chau market and wholesale some vegetables and send them there. "
